#3.

(ggplot(df, 
        aes(x = "income", y = "life_exp", fill = "four_regions", size = "population")) 
 + annotate('text', x = 10000, y = 64.5, label = '2010', color = 'gray', size = 200, alpha = 0.2)
 + geom_point(alpha = 0.8, stroke = 0.25)   
 + scale_size(range = [2, 27])
 + guides(size = False) 
 + scale_y_continuous(breaks = [0, 20, 30, 40, 50, 60, 70, 80, 90])
 + scale_x_continuous(breaks = [0, 500, 1000, 2000, 4000, 8000, 16000, 32000, 64000],
                      trans = "log10")
 + theme(figure_size = (10,5), 
         panel_background = element_rect(fill = 'white'), 
         panel_grid = element_line(color = 'gray', size = 0.5, linetype = 'solid'), 
         panel_grid_minor = element_blank()) 
 + labs(x = "Income", y = "Life Expectancy", fill = "4 Regions of the World")
 + scale_fill_manual(values = ["cyan", "chartreuse", "tomato", "gold"]))

#4.

(ggplot(df, aes(y = "income", x = "life_exp", fill = "four_regions"))
 + geom_boxplot() 
 + scale_y_continuous(breaks = [0, 8000, 16000, 24000, 32000, 40000, 48000, 56000, 64000,
                               72000, 80000, 88000, 96000])
 + labs(y = "Income", x = "Life Expectancy", fill = "4 Regions of the World"))

<Figure Size: (640 x 480)>

Geom boxplot is a geometry that is good for comparing the distributions between groups. This geometry is strong because it conveys a similar message to the scatterplot. In general, life expectancy increase is correlated to an increase in Income. However, this geometry cannot accomodate a 4th variable for visualization without becoming too distracting.

#3.

(ggplot(df2, 
        aes(x = "exports", y = "imports", fill = "four_regions", size = "energy")) 
 + annotate('text', x = 80, y = 64.5, label = '1997', color = 'gray', size = 160, alpha = 0.2)
 + geom_point(alpha = 0.8, stroke = 0.25) 
 + guides(size = False)
 + scale_size(range = [2, 18])
 + scale_x_continuous(breaks = [0, 20, 40, 60, 80, 100, 120, 140, 160, 180, 200])
 + scale_y_continuous(breaks = [0, 50, 100, 150, 200, 250, 300, 350, 400])
 + theme(figure_size = (10,5), panel_background = element_rect(fill = 'white'), 
         panel_grid = element_line(color = 'gray', size = 0.5, linetype = 'solid')) 
 + labs(x = "Exports (\% of GDP)", y = "Imports (\% of GDP)", fill = "4 Regions of the World")
 + scale_fill_manual(values = ["cyan", "chartreuse", "tomato", "gold"]))

<Figure Size: (1000 x 500)>
#4.

(ggplot(df2, 
        aes(x = "exports", y = "imports", fill = "energy", size = 3)) 
 + geom_jitter() 
 + geom_smooth(method = 'lm', color='black', size = 1)
 + guides(size = False)
 + theme(figure_size = (10,10), panel_background = element_rect(fill = 'white'), 
         panel_grid = element_line(color = 'gray', linetype = 'solid')) 
 + labs(x = "Exports (\% of GDP)", y = "Imports (\% of GDP)", fill = "Energy Usage")
 + facet_wrap("four_regions"))

<Figure Size: (1000 x 1000)>

Geom Jitter is almost the same as geom point but reduces overlap of points compared to geom point. Geom smooth is a geometry that can be used to plot the line of best fit. I believe this is a good geometry because of how much overlap we have and it is interesting to see the least squares regression between the 2 variables. It is difficult to accomodate all 4 variables as the energy scale fill color makes it difficult to discern.

#3.

(ggplot(df3, 
        aes(x = "internet_users", y = "gdp", fill = "four_regions", size = "income")) 
 + annotate('text', x = 40, y = 5000, label = '2001', color = 'gray', size = 150, alpha = 0.3)
 + geom_point(alpha = 0.9) 
 + scale_size(range = [3, 16])
 + guides(size = False)
 + scale_x_continuous(breaks = [0, 10, 20, 30, 40, 50, 60, 70, 80])
 + scale_y_continuous(breaks = [200, 500, 1000, 5000, 10000, 20000, 50000, 100000], 
                      labels = ["200", "500", "1000", "5000", "10k", "20k", "50k", "100k"],
                      trans = "log10")
 + theme(figure_size = (10,5), panel_background = element_rect(fill = 'white'), panel_grid_minor = element_blank(),
         panel_grid = element_line(color = 'gray', linetype = 'solid')) 
 + labs(x = "Individuals using the Internet", y = "GDP/Capita", fill = "4 Regions of the World")
 + scale_fill_manual(values = ["cyan", "chartreuse", "tomato", "gold"]))

Geom violin shows a violin plot that is used to compare the distributions of the variables by region of the world. The violin plot is visual focused and shows the shape/spread. This geometry is good, but cannot be used to accomodate another variable like income without negatively affecting the focus of the visualization.
